#We can create our own functions to perform specific tasks
#Define your own function using def followed by the function name and parentheses. Parentheses can use parameters to pass information into the function. Coluns: indicate the start of the function 
#Every line of code that is indented after the function is part of that function and will be executed when the function is called (the space between () and : is important)

# Recap functions and variables (string = text and integer = number)

#Create the variable name and assign it to input function
name = input("What is your name?")
#Input is stored in the variable name 
#Must use f to insert variable into the function print's string (that is to be printed 
print(f"Hello {name}") 

#Ask for the users age with a string and convert the input to an integer 
age = int(input("What is your age? "))

# Now we will create our own function using def 
def hello():
    print(f"Okay so your name is {name} and you are {age} years old. Got it")

#We have created the function and now we will call it so it runs
hello()

#We create a new variable called question and fill it with the users answer using the input function 
question = input("What question can I help you with? ")

#Repeat our function and print the question variable - we can not simply add the question variable to the function because it is not defined. We need to call the function again and then print the new variable seperately 
print(f"Let us answer your question: {question}")

#Now we will create a function that takes in a parameter (a variable that is passed into the function when it is called) - this way the function can be used for different inputs and is not fixed on the specific variables we created earlier
#The function previously was not flexible and required the variables to be defined before the function was called - now we will create a function that takes in parameters (a variable that is passed into the function when it is called) - this way the function can be used for different inputs and is not fixed on the specific variables we created earlier

#The new function uses the value passed into it when it is called and does not require variables to be defined before the function is called 
#This refers to "scope" - a variable only existing within the context you define it in - the function can only access variables that are defined within the function or passed into it as parameters  

def answer_question(name, question):
    print(f"Okay {name}, so to answer {question} I will need to do some research first") 

answer_question(name, question)

